post_text: Today we celebrate #Juneteenth, which commemorates the freeing of slaves in Texas two and a half years after President Abraham Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation. On this day in 1865, Union Major General Gordon Granger entered Galveston, Texas, and made official the emancipation of all enslaved African Americans in the city. The quest for the fair treatment of all people, justice and equal treatment under the law continues to this day. As Martin Luther King, Jr. so eloquently stated, "Change does not roll in on the wheels of inevitability, but comes through continuous struggle."

post_text:
More details on Joe Walker STEALTH Academy's efforts to support the community. Matt Anderson, one of our Project Lead the Way teachers, and Karou Thomas, our MakerSpace teacher, have been using our 3D printers to make adjustable headbands for use with N95 and surgical masks to alleviate the pain of having the straps behind your ears all day long. To date, they have printed over 200 of them and handed them off to:
A.V. Hospital, Quartz Hill Urgent Care, Quartz Hill Pharmacy, Edwards Air Force Base, and have orders coming in from Ohio, and other health care facilities in the AV. What a cool way for Joe Walker staff to give back to our community.

post_text: Out of an abundance of caution, the Westside Union School District Board of Trustees met and unanimously voted this morning to extend the closure of all Westside schools until May 5. State and County officials are scheduled to provide an updated assessment on April 19. At that time, the Board may extend the closures should it be deemed necessary after the review. We will continue to provide updates to the public as more information becomes available.
text: Out of an abundance of caution, the Westside Union School District Board of Trustees met and unanimously voted this morning to extend the closure of all Westside schools until May 5. State and County officials are scheduled to provide an updated assessment on April 19. At that time, the Board may extend the closures should it be deemed necessary after the review. We will continue to provide updates to the public as more information becomes available.

post_text: On Wednesday, March 18th, Hillview will be holding our annual open house event. We will kick things off at 5:30pm with our 6th Grade Honors Academy parent information event in our cafeteria. That meeting is for families interested in the 6th grade program for the 2020-21 school year. From 6:00  7:00pm, we will have our main open house event in the gym and some select classrooms. All students are invited to the main event at 6:00pm; however, it is geared more towards incoming 7th graders and current 7th graders. If you have a child that will be attending Hillview next year, we hope you can join us!

Former Congressman Steve Knight came and spoke about his father and the service of our vets. He reminded everyone that he attended Rancho Vista when he was a student.

Go Rockets!

post_text:
Rancho Vista's Student Council has been busy!

They are so excited to be asked to help out with Rancho Vistas new Little Free Libraries! On Wednesday, they had District Office employees and members of the Lancaster Rotary come to install two of these libraries, one for primary grades and one for upper grades. The Student Council officers helped with the installation, and on Thursday the whole student council helped fill them with books. Thanks to Lancaster Rotary for donating and painting (AMAZINGLY!) the libraries as well as books to fill them with. Rancho Vista will continue to accept book donations to help keep them well stocked. Thanks to those who have already donated!

post_text:
The Hillview Middle School Functional Skills Program collaborated with Palmdale Sheriffs Station to coordinate a presentation for our students. Officer Sneed visited the classes and helped teach on various community safety topics. He discussed with our students what to do if youre in trouble, how to make a 911 call and give appropriate information, and the role of police officers in our community.

He was able to bring along with him some common items he uses in his line of work for students to see and hold. After the presentation, students were able to go inside a couple of the police cars, explore them, ask questions, and see, use, and hold other job related items. We are so grateful to Offer Sneed and the Palmdale Sheriffs Station for taking the time to help teach our students!

We would like to invite you to participate in this years California School Parent Survey, developed by WestEd at the direction of the California Department of Education. This survey is an opportunity to communicate your perceptions about your students school. While participation is voluntary we hope that you will choose to participated because your input is important to us. The information you provide will help guide district and school efforts to promote safety, enhance learning supports, and improve student achievement. A link to the survey can be found on your schools website: https://www.westside.k12.ca.us/schools.
The link will be active through January 17th. Thank you in advance for your participation.

post_text:
Congratulations to Hillviews Model United Nations team who competed at Tustin High Schools 27th Model United Nations conference on November 23rd. Students represented countries as delegates and competed against other students from throughout Southern California.

Hillview students wrote position papers before the conference and, while in committee, delivered speeches, wrote resolutions, and caucused with other delegates. Students participated in the UNODC (United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime) and UNEP (United Nations Environment Programme) committees that addressed Global Drug Trafficking and Pollution of Freshwater.

Way to go Hawks!

post_text:
The 2nd Annual Inclusion Sports Soccer Tournament was held yesterday. The event saw Hillview battling it out on the field against Joe Walker. Inclusion sports is an extra-curricular activity that takes place at both schools, in which our students in special education play alongside a peer coach. Joe Walker defeated Hillview 5-0.

The success of the program led to Hillview being named a Unified Champion School by the Special Olympics organization last spring. Congratulations to both teams for a great season!

Congratulations to the 5th grade IDEA Academy @ Cottonwood students who graduated Wednesday from the STARBASE stem program.

The students completed 25 hours of training with members of Edwards Air Force Base personnel for the STARBASE Edwards program. MESSAGE FOR LEONA VALLEY FAMILIES:

Good Morning Leona Valley Families,

As many of you have heard on the news, strong Santa Ana winds are expected again in Southern California.

We have been notified that Leona Valley School is located in an area that may be subject to a power outage. At this time, we do not know when or if that may happen. School will open and we are hopeful to maintain our regular school day. However, if a power outage is called, we will need to send students home.

The power outage may also impact the homes in the area surrounding the school, so if you havent done so, you may want to take time to prepare.

Thank you for understanding this situation. I am hopeful to see your child in school today. If you have other questions, please feel free to call us.

MESSAGE TO JOE WALKER MIDDLE SCHOOL & LEONA VALLEY ELEMENTARY FAMILIES:

Good Morning,

As many of you have heard on the news, strong Santa Ana winds are expected in Southern California today and tomorrow. Since there were so many devastating fires last season, as a precaution, Edison Company has identified areas where power may be turned off to prevent wildfires.

We have been notified that Joe Walker Middle School and Leona Valley Elementary are located in an area that may be subject to a power outage. At this time, we do not know when or if that may happen. School will open and we are hopeful to maintain our regular school day and other activities as usual. However, if a power outage is called, we will need to send students home.

The power outage may also impact the homes in the area surrounding the schools, so if you havent done so, you may want to take time to prepare.

Thank you for understanding this situation. We are hopeful to see your child in school today and tomorrow. If you have other questions, please feel free to call us.
